  "prompt": "How is RMM calculated in chemistry?",
  "response": "In chemistry, RMM stands for Relative Molecular Mass (also known as Molecular Weight). It is calculated by following these steps:\n\n1. Identify the elements in the molecule\n\n2. Find the atomic mass of each element from the periodic table\n\n3. Multiply each element's atomic mass by its number of atoms in the molecule\n\n4. Sum all these values\n\nExample calculation for water (H2O):\n- Hydrogen (H): 1.008 \u00d7 2 = 2.016\n- Oxygen (O): 16.00 \u00d7 1 = 16.00\n- RMM = 2.016 + 16.00 = 18.016 g/mol\n\nKey points:\n- Expressed in grams per mole (g/mol)\n- Uses atomic masses from periodic table\n- Accounts for number of atoms of each element\n- Helps determine molar mass and chemical calculations\n\nThe formula can be generically represented as:\nRMM = \u03a3(atomic mass \u00d7 number of atoms)",
